Extra graphs 2023 week 08 regular vs Tennessee

If you would like to see and play with the interactive version of these graphs you can find them at https://github.com/MCurve7/mcurve7_cfb/tree/main/RBR/2023 You just need to download the Alabama_(year)_regular_wk??_(opponent).html file and open it in a web browser.

Well that certainly wasn't a rollercoaster of emotions, but an elevator ride from the floor level to the subbasement up to the penthouse. There was a moment where it looked like we were "heading on up" on drives 5 and 6, but the end of our 6th drive landed us back into the subbasement.

Comparing our SR by Drive charts the most obvious 1st half observations are our two turnovers and them bookending the half with TDs. I'm still not sure what to make of the mean SR by Drive vs the game SR, but our μ_game(SR by Drive) = 0.383 and SR = 0.397 which is clearly pretty close. Our μ_game(SR by Drive) = 0.383 was pretty close to our μ_season(SR by Drive) = 0.364 and maybe this makes sense given that we played about the same way we play most games which is basically good half/bad half.

They had a SR = 0.380, but μ_game(SR by Drive) = 0.268 which is a pretty big difference. For how uncomfortable that first half was, they really only had three long drives (1, 3, 7) and a short field on drive 4 due to a fumble. Their scoring drives had SRs of 0.625 and 0.600 and their 14 play third drive SR was down to 0.500 with the rest 0.250 or 0. So I'd say our defense was playing pretty well for the most part in the first half and kicked it up a notch in the second.

I have run a few other seasons and hope to compare the Distance to 1st/TD, Yards gained statistics by Down results to what we're seeing this year. Just a cursory view of the historic data it looks like I'm not seeing the decreasing values like I thought I would. Unlike other recent games our mean/median distance to 1st/TD did decrease by down like I would think it should if you are having a good performance. Looking at the Yards to Success vs Yards Gained by Down 2nd down data and wow, we were only successful on 4 out of 20 plays! But looking at 1st down we were successful on 16/30 with 9 1st/TDs. On 3rd down we were 5/13. It almost makes me want to split all of these charts out by half just to see what it would look like.

Fortunately there isn't much to say about penalties this week other than there was only one Alabama penalty. Tennessee on the other hand had 8 penalties. Unfortunately the Tennessee game data isn't allowing me to pull their penalties out so I don't have a graph for them for the season. I do have an alternate source for the number of enforced penalties and as can be seen from the table below they are the most penalized team in the SEC. So maybe Heupel should whine less and get his team to play more disciplined. Last season Tennessee finished with a z-score of 1.86 and this season now has a z-score of 1.69.

I know everyone complains about our penalties but we have a z-score of -0.29 this season. This is down quite a bit from the z-score of 1.67 from last season. The 10 vs Texas and 14 vs Texas A&M were quite a lot (everything is bigger when playing Texas?), but the rest of our games haven't been bad. I'd still love to see 0 penalties, but the only SEC team with a 0 penalty game is Arkansas in week 5.
